<subsection xml:id="subsec-forming-quadratic-equations-from-different-situations">
    <title>Forming Quadratic Equations From Different Situations</title>
    <p>
        In this section, we will learn how to form quadratic equations from different situations.
    </p>

    <!--Descriprion-->
    <p>
        Quadratic expressions are formed from algebraic terms that involve a variable raised to the second power (i.e., <m>x^2</m> ) along with other terms involving the variable and constants. 
        The general form of a quadratic expression is:
        <me>
            ax^2 + bx + c
        </me>        
    </p>
    <p>
        where <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> are constants and <m>x</m> is the variable.
        and <m>a \neq 0</m>, because if <m>a</m> is equal to zero, then the expression will become linear.
    </p>

    <!--Teaching/Learning Example-->
    <p>
        Quadratic expressions can be form through expanding  quadratic expressions. 
        Take for example the quadratic expression <m>(x + 3)(x + 5)</m>, we can expand this expression to form a quadratic expression.
    </p>
    <p>
        To expand the expression <m>(x + 3)(x + 5)</m>, we multiply the two  expressions.
    </p>
    <p>
        <md>
            <mrow> (x + 3)(x + 5) = \amp x^2 + 5x + 3x + 15 </mrow>
        </md>
    </p>
    <p>
        Collecting like terms together we form;
    </p>
    <p>
        <md>
            <mrow> = \amp x^2 + 8x + 15 </mrow>
        </md>
    </p>
    <p>
        Thus the expanded form of expression <m>(x + 3)(x + 5)</m> is;
        <md>
            <mrow> = \amp x^2 + 8x + 15 </mrow>
        </md>
    </p>
    <!--Methods to be applied in teaching/Learning-->
    <p>
        Quadratic expressions can be formed in a variety of ways, typically through expansion, factoring, or completing the square. 
        Below are examples are common methods for forming quadratic expressions:
    </p>

    <p>
       <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
                Expansion method
            </p>
            <p>
                This method involves multiplying two binomials to form a quadratic expression.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Using square of a binomial
            </p>
            <p>
                This method involves squaring a binomial to form a quadratic expression.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Factoring method
            </p>
            <p>
                This method involves factoring a quadratic expression to form a quadratic expression.
            </p>
        </li>
       </ul> 
    </p>

    <!--Examples-->
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Form a quadratic expression using the expansion method.
                <me>
                    (x + 2)(x + 3)
                </me>                
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To form a quadratic expression using the expansion method, we multiply the two binomials:
                <md>
                    <mrow> (x + 2)(x + 3) = \amp x^2 + 3x + 2x + 6  </mrow>
                </md>            
            </p>
            <p>
                Collecting like terms together we form;
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \amp x^2 + 5x + 6 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                
                Thus the expanded form of expression <m>(x + 2)(x + 3)</m> is;
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    x^2 + 5x + 6
                </me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Form a quadratic expression using the square of a binomial.
                <me>
                    (x + 2)^2
                </me>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To form a quadratic expression using the square of a binomial, we square the binomial:
                <md>
                    <mrow> (x + 2)^2 = \amp (x + 2)(x + 2) </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Expanding the binomial we get;
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \amp x^2 + 2x + 2x + 4 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Collecting like terms together we form;
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \amp x^2 + 4x + 4 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Thus the expanded form of expression <m>(x + 2)^2</m> is;
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \amp  x^2 + 4x + 4 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

     <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Form a quadratic expression using the factoring method.
                <me>
                    6x^2 + 12x
                </me>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To form a quadratic expression using the factoring method, we factor out the common factor:
                The  commoni factor of <m>6x^2</m> and <m>12x</m> is <m>6x</m>
                <md>
                    <mrow> 6x^2 + 12x = \amp 6x(x + 2) </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Thus the factored form of expression <m>6x^2 + 12x</m> is;
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    6x(x + 2)
                </me>
            </p>
        </solution>
     </example>
    

